Input.name: Volksdeutsche Mittelstelle (VoMi)
Answer.Ans1: The Coordination Center for Ethnic Germans (Volksdeutsche Mittelstelle) was founded approximately 86 years ago. It was established around 1937. The agency was created by the National Socialist German Workers' Party (NSDAP) to oversee and coordinate the affairs of ethnic Germans living outside of Germany. The primary objective of the agency was to strengthen the bond between Germany and ethnic Germans living in other countries, particularly those in Eastern Europe.
Answer.Res1: The Coordination Center for Ethnic Germans was founded by the National Socialist German Workers' Party (NSDAP) as part of their broader ideology and policies related to ethnic nationalism and expansionism. The NSDAP sought to establish and maintain cultural, political, and demographic connections with ethnic Germans living outside of Germany, particularly in Eastern European countries. The agency was seen as a tool to facilitate the integration and loyalty of these ethnic Germans to Nazi Germany. By coordinating various initiatives and providing support to ethnic German communities, the NSDAP aimed to strengthen its influence and extend its sphere of control.
